{
=APIPA\: 169.254.x.x — automatically assigned when DHCP fails.
~Loopback/Localhost\: 127.0.0.1 — tests the local network stack.
~If a device has a 169.254.x.x address, it cannot reach the DHCP server. This is the first thing to check when a user reports "no internet connection." Verify the DHCP server is running and the physical connection is good. Subnetting Quick Reference (CIDR Cheat Sheet) CIDR Subnet Mask Network Bits Host Bits Total Addresses Usable Hosts /24 255.255.255.0 24 8 256 254 /25 255.255.255.128 25 7 128 126 /26 255.255.255.192 26 6 64 62 /27 255.255.255.224 27 5 32 30 /28 255.255.255.240 28 4 16 14 /29 255.255.255.248 29 3 8 6 /30 255.255.255.252 30 2 4 2 Formula\: Usable Hosts \= 2^(host bits) - 2
~The Magic Number Method\: Subtract the last non-zero octet of the subnet mask from 256 to find the block size. For /26 (255.255.255.192)\: 256 - 192 \= 64. Subnets start at 0, 64, 128, 192. If a host has IP 192.168.1.75 with /26, it is in the 192.168.1.64 subnet (range .64-.127).
}

::n10009_1_8_sg1 [n10009_1_8] Summarize evolving use cases for modern network environments ::
For N10-009 objective 1.8, which statement best applies to\: Summarize evolving use cases for modern network environments?
{
=SDN (Software-Defined Networking)\: Separates the control plane (routing decisions) from the data plane (packet forwarding). Centralized controller manages the network programmatically.
~SD-WAN\: Applies SDN principles to WAN connections; application-aware, transport-agnostic.
~Zero Trust Architecture (ZTA)\: "Never trust, always verify." No user or device is trusted by default, even inside the network perimeter. Key principles\: least privilege, micro-segmentation.
~SASE (Secure Access Service Edge)\: Combines network security (SWG, CASB, ZTNA) with WAN capabilities (SD-WAN) in a single cloud-delivered service.
}

::n10009_1_8_sg2 [n10009_1_8] Summarize evolving use cases for modern network environments ::
For N10-009 objective 1.8, which statement best applies to\: Summarize evolving use cases for modern network environments?
{
=SD-WAN\: Applies SDN principles to WAN connections; application-aware, transport-agnostic.
~SDN (Software-Defined Networking)\: Separates the control plane (routing decisions) from the data plane (packet forwarding). Centralized controller manages the network programmatically.
~Zero Trust Architecture (ZTA)\: "Never trust, always verify." No user or device is trusted by default, even inside the network perimeter. Key principles\: least privilege, micro-segmentation.
~SASE (Secure Access Service Edge)\: Combines network security (SWG, CASB, ZTNA) with WAN capabilities (SD-WAN) in a single cloud-delivered service.
}

::n10009_2_2_sg1 [n10009_2_2] Given a scenario, configure switching technologies and featu ::
For N10-009 objective 2.2, which statement best applies to\: Given a scenario, configure switching technologies and features?
{
=VLAN\: Logically segments a physical network into separate broadcast domains.
~Native VLAN\: Untagged traffic on an 802.1Q trunk port. Default is VLAN 1 — change it for security.
~Voice VLAN\: A separate VLAN for VoIP traffic to ensure QoS prioritization.
~802.1Q Tagging\: IEEE standard for VLAN tagging on trunk ports.
}

::n10009_2_2_sg2 [n10009_2_2] Given a scenario, configure switching technologies and featu ::
